expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2479</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00N4</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00N4.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Counting <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injections</fr:link> between <fr:link
href="jms-00LX.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00LX">finite sets</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:link
href="jms-00LX.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00LX">finite sets</fr:link> <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>B</fr:tex>, we can describe number of <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injections</fr:link> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block">   \mathord { \# } { \mathrm {Inj} { \mathopen {} \left ( A , B \right ) \mathclose {}} } =   \begin {cases}   { \mathord { \# } {B} \choose \mathord { \# } {A}} \cdot   { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathord { \# } {A} \right ) \mathclose {}} ! &amp; \text {when }  \mathord { \# } {A} \leq   \mathord { \# } {B}    \\    0 &amp; \text {otherwise}   \end {cases} </fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2477</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00N4</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>An <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injection</fr:link> <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> associates no more than one <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex> to the same <fr:tex>b \in  B</fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex>U \subseteq  B</fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex>f { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>as each <fr:tex>b \in  U</fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> that is in <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex>\mathord { \# } {B} \choose   \mathord { \# } {A}</fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00KT"
href="jms-00KT.xml"
taxon="Proposition"></fr:ref> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathord { \# } {A}! \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
